## 1. The Textual Evidence

Three scriptural passages point toward the same structural situation, approached from different angles.

**Hebrews 11:39-40**: The author has catalogued the saints of Israel — Abel, Enoch, Abraham, Moses, the prophets — and concludes: "These were all commended for their faith, yet none of them received what had been promised, since God had planned something better for us so that only together with us would they be made perfect."

"Only together with us would they be made perfect." The perfecting is simultaneous. Their completion waited on something that had not yet occurred. They were not made perfect progressively, in sequence, as each died. They waited, together, for a single event that would complete them all at once.

**Matthew 27:52-53**: At the moment of Christ's death, "the tombs broke open. The bodies of many holy people who had died were raised to life. They came out of the tombs after his resurrection and went into the holy city and appeared to many people."

This is not the general resurrection. It is a specific, bounded event — "many holy people," not all, and specifically at the moment of the Resurrection. The raising is localized and immediate, tied to the Release event rather than distributed across subsequent time.

**1 Peter 3:18-20**: Christ, "being put to death in the flesh but made alive in the spirit... went and proclaimed to the spirits in prison, who disobeyed long ago."

Whatever the full interpretation of this passage, it establishes that between death and Resurrection, Christ extended some form of Φ-proximate contact to beings held in a waiting condition. The proclamation is not evangelism (these are not uninformed beings). It is something structural being made available to beings who had been waiting for it.

The framework has a full structural account of what was happening, what the waiting condition was, and why its resolution required exactly this sequence.

