## 6. The Structural Significance of the Timing

The three blocking conditions resolve in structural order, not in arbitrary sequence. This is significant.

They could not resolve until the Son had completed the kenotic traversal. That traversal required thirty-three years at H₄₈ amplitude — not because God needed thirty-three years, but because the kenotic constraint, once accepted, governed the pace of the traversal. The full traversal had to occur within H₄₈ according to H₄₈ constraints: birth, growth, ministry, death.

The waiting of the pre-Incarnation saints is therefore not a design inefficiency. It is the structural consequence of the kenotic constraint that makes the traversal possible at all. The Son could not both accept full H₄₈ constraints and instantaneously resolve them. The acceptance of the constraint is what gives the traversal its weight — the demonstration is only a demonstration because it happened in H₄₈ time, under H₄₈ conditions, without the amplitude that would have made it trivial.

The waiting of the saints is the shadow of the kenotic constraint falling backward through time. They are waiting because the event that will release them is itself constrained to occur in time, and time is proceeding at H₄₈ pace.

Hebrews 11:39-40 names this precisely: they were not made perfect ahead of the event. The event completed them together with the first community of its beneficiaries. The sequence is not inefficiency; it is structural.

